value.value: cardiovascular structural anomaly in which the aorta arises from the right ventricle while the pulmonary artery arises from the left ventricle
any structural anomaly of any of the arteries that branch from the ascending aorta to supply blood to the heart
any structural anomaly of the small diameter vessels that branch from the arteries and lead to the capillaries

any structural anomaly of the convex portion of the aorta between the ascending and descending parts of the aorta; branches from it include the brachiocephalic trunk, the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery; the brachiocephalic trunk further splits to form the right subclavian artery and the right common carotid artery

definition.value: Note that this term refers to the adult aortic arch structure. For multiple aortic arches present in the embryo, see the term for embryonic aortic arches [abnormal branchial arch artery morphology; MP:0002672].

value.value: any structural anomaly of the small nodular mass of specialized muscle fibers located in the interatrial septum near the opening of the coronary sinus; this node gives rise to the electrical connection between the atria and ventricles and responds to the sinoatrial node

any structural anomaly of the small mass of modified cardiac muscle fibers located at the junction of the superior vena cava and the right atrium that is the source of contraction impulses for the heart
anomaly in the transfer of cardiac electrical impulses through the specialized cardiac muscle fibers that originates in the atrioventricular node and extends into the ventricle
any structural anomaly of the specialized cardiac muscle fibers that originates in the atrioventricular node and extends into the ventricle
any structural anomaly in the sensory nerve endings in the wall of the atria of the heart, vena cava, aortic arch and carotid sinus that are sensitive to changes in blood pressure
excessively low concentrations of potassium in the circulating blood; may be chronic or due to gastrointestinal and kidney depletion due to infection
inadequate blood flow to the heart; may cause infarction and is usually caused by coronary artery disease
any structural anomaly in the plasma membrane of a muscle fiber that is capable of conducting electrical impulses
any anomaly in the normal phenomenon of mild acceleration and slowing of the heart rate that occurs during the respiratory cycle

any structural anomaly in the impulse-conducting system composed of modified cardiac muscle and having the power of spontaneous rhythmicity and conduction more highly developed than the rest of the heart
any structural anomaly in the cardiac muscle fibers composing the terminal portion of the heart conduction system located in the ventricle
any structural anomaly of the minute vessels that collect deoxygenated blood from the capillary plexuses returns it to the veins
reduced thickness of the irregular layer of loose connective tissue containing fibroblasts, adipose cells, and macrophages, that is immediately deep to the skin and superficial to the deep fascia
increase in the width of the irregular layer of loose connective tissue containing fibroblasts, adipose cells, and macrophages, that is immediately deep to the skin and superficial to the deep fascia
anomaly in the ratio of the volume of carbon dioxide released to oxygen consumed by a body tissue or an organism compared to controls
anomaly in the ability of muscle cells to take in glucose

any structural anomaly of the cilia of the embryo found on the cells of the embryonic node, which generate flow of extraembryonic fluid surrounding the node in a distinct twirling motion that directs fluid flow asymmetrically across the cellular surface to affect asymmetric body plan organization
absence of cilia on the cells of the embryonic node
abnormal arrangement of organs or parts of the body in relation to each other according to the left-right axis
any structural anomaly of the part of the body between the neck and the abdomen
aberration in the differentiation of the mammary gland during early embryogenesis
any structural anomaly of the muscular portion of the tongue

label.value: abnormal gastric surface mucous cell morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the mucus secreting epithelial cells that line the luminal surface of the stomach and the gastric pits which secrete mucus and HCO3- to protect the gastric surface from the acidic environment of the stomach
any structural anomaly of the mucin-producing epithelial cells present in the neck of the gastric glands
any structural anomaly of the gastric acid producing epithelial cells that are distributed throughout the length of the gastric gland
any structural anomaly of the pepsinogen producing epithelial cells that are clustered at the base of the gastric gland
any structural anomaly of the various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting epithelial cells present throughout the mucosa of the digestive tract
anomaly in the resting tautness or laxity of a muscle, normally somewhere in the middle of the range between total contraction and total relaxation
increased muscle tension resulting in stiffness of the muscles in the resting state
decreased muscle tension resulting in limpness of the muscles in the resting state, not to be confused with weakness
any functional anomaly of the musculature as it relates to electrical phenomena
missing the band in the center of the H band that contains proteins that crosslink the thick filament system (myosins) and the M-band part of the elastic filaments
elevated concentration of porphyrins or protoporphyrins
thicker than normal superficial layer of compact bone
increased ability of bone to endure the application of force without yielding or breaking
absence of the small pockets, vesicles, caves, or recesses communicating with the outside of a cell and extending inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane
less than the normal concentration of iron in the blood

definition.value: Serum iron measures the total amount of iron in the blood, nearly all of which is bound to transferrin.

value.value: anomalous blood concentration of the metallic element that normally occurs in the heme of hemoglobin, myoglobin, transferrin, ferritin, and iron-containing porphyrins; it is an essential component of enzymes such as catalase, peroxidase, and various cytochromes

definition.value: Serum iron measures the total amount of iron in the blood, nearly all of which is bound to transferrin.

value.value: increase in the number of renal tubule cells undergoing programmed cell death
morphological changes resulting from pathological death of renal tubular tissue; usually due to irreversible damage
reduced or absent inflammatory response in the pancreatic tissue after experimental manipulation

anomaly in the index of beat-to-beat QT interval fluctuations (temporal QT interval variability), normally expressed as a unitless negative number reflecting beat-to-beat changes in ventricular repolarization; an increased, positive QTVI number indicates significant repolarization abnormalities

complete discontinuation/blockage between the ascending and descending aorta; includes Type A, interruption distal to the subclavian artery that is ipsilateral to the second carotid artery, and Type B, interruption between second carotid artery and ipsilateral subclavian artery
the aortic arch lies to the right of the trachea and esophagus; results from persistence of the entire right dorsal arch and involution of a segment of the left arch
defect in which the main aorta tube splits into large left and right branches (right and left aortic arches), encircling the trachea and esophagus, before becoming one tube to go to the lower body
the subclavian artery aberrantly originates from the aortic arch distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery, i.e., it is the last branch of the aortic arch
